findings.recommendation:
In addition to storing lockout_until timestamp, also store lockout_set_at timestamp. On each unlock attempt, verify: (1) if currentTime < lockout_until → still locked; (2) if currentTime < lockout_set_at → clock was set backward → treat as still locked (do NOT clear the lockout). Only clear the lockout if currentTime >= lockout_until AND currentTime >= lockout_set_at. This makes backward clock manipulation ineffective. Example:

```kotlin
val lockoutUntil = storage.getLong(KEY_LOCKOUT_UNTIL, 0L)
val lockoutSetAt = storage.getLong(KEY_LOCKOUT_SET_AT, 0L)
val now = timeProvider.currentTimeMillis()
if (now < lockoutSetAt) {
    // Clock moved backward — maintain lockout
    return AuthResult.LockedOut(lockoutUntil)
}
if (now < lockoutUntil) {
    return AuthResult.LockedOut(lockoutUntil)
}
// Lockout expired — proceed
```

Implement separate handling for biometric authentication outcomes:

```kotlin
object : BiometricPrompt.AuthenticationCallback() {
    override fun onAuthenticationFailed() {
        // Wrong biometric presented — increment biometric failure count only
        biometricFailureCount++
        if (biometricFailureCount >= 3) showPasswordPrompt()
    }
    override fun onAuthenticationError(errorCode: Int, errString: CharSequence) {
        when (errorCode) {
            BiometricPrompt.ERROR_NEGATIVE_BUTTON,
            BiometricPrompt.ERROR_USER_CANCELED -> {
                // User chose to cancel or use password — show password prompt
                // Do NOT increment failure counter
                showPasswordPrompt()
            }
            BiometricPrompt.ERROR_LOCKOUT,
            BiometricPrompt.ERROR_LOCKOUT_PERMANENT -> {
                // System-level biometric lockout — fall back to password immediately
                showPasswordPrompt()
            }
            else -> {
                // Hardware error — show error message, allow retry
            }
        }
    }
}
```
Note: BiometricPrompt.ERROR_LOCKOUT (7) and ERROR_LOCKOUT_PERMANENT (9) from the system should also trigger fallback to password, not count as incremental failures.

Use ProcessLifecycleOwner for background detection instead of Activity lifecycle callbacks. ProcessLifecycleOwner's ON_STOP event fires only when the app is truly backgrounded (all activities hidden), not on configuration changes or split-screen:

```kotlin
class AuthManager @Inject constructor(...) : DefaultLifecycleObserver {
    init {
        // Register with process lifecycle, not activity lifecycle
        ProcessLifecycleOwner.get().lifecycle.addObserver(this)
    }
    override fun onStop(owner: LifecycleOwner) {
        backgroundTimestamp = timeProvider.currentTimeMillis()
    }
    override fun onStart(owner: LifecycleOwner) {
        val elapsed = timeProvider.currentTimeMillis() - backgroundTimestamp
        if (elapsed > BACKGROUND_LOCK_THRESHOLD_MS) lock()
        backgroundTimestamp = 0L
    }
}
```
This correctly handles rotation (onStop is not called), split-screen (onStop IS called when wallet is in background position), and multi-window scenarios.

